Just 24 hours in the new McLaren Artura and I love it!
I think Hybrid is the best option for me.
I can glide around town in Electric Mode up to 81mph which weirdly enough felt fast and cool.
Then I switch (using the new configuration for the traction and drive modes right by your fingers by the wheel) to sport and the car changes not only its sound obviously, but it’s entire attitude!
V6 twin-turbo 577 BHP kicks into action.
It’s a growling, fabulous sports car just begging me to do what I do.
So I did it.
Yes, it’s Hybrid for me!

#mclaren #mclarenartura #supercar #racing #hybrid #mclarenhybrid

Why a hybrid makes me happy:
It’s rather like choosing the right diet for my lifestyle.
I struggled to be a vegan, way too many restrictions and not that fun.
So now I eat a little meat and fish, but have vegan options on occasion just to balance things out.
I get the pleasure of both worlds.
Get it?
This McLaren Artura allows me to cruise LA at decent speed in full Electric mode (while looking sharp) but being a mindful responsible human.
Then I flick a switch and it’s as though I’m having roast beef with all the trimmings! 
Fucking fabulous.
Makes me feel life as I choose to live!
Then ‘swoosh’ and I’m back passing speed checks like the silent good citizen I am…;)
Congratulations McLaren on giving us this lovely alternative.
JB

#mclaren #mclarenartura #supercar #hybrid #sportscar #review

I just heard the sad  news that Lady Susie Moss passed away, which is the end of one of the most beautiful love affairs I’ve ever witnessed. Her support of Stirling was inspirational to see, her love for him so deep, and their obvious affection, humor and passion for each other was contagious.
So many great memories for our family with the two of them, which will last us forever.
I took this portrait of them at the Goodwood Festival of Speed a few years ago, and it hangs in my house as one of the most intimate moments I’ve ever captured. 
It was the end of the day, Stirling was tired as we all walked back into Goodwood House for the prize giving. So I found him a chair and together they watched the ceremony through the window. I quietly took the picture as she stood with her hand on his shoulder, always there as she seemed to be, giving him the support he needed.

I’m happy the two of you are back together now, as you have been waiting for.
Jbx

I am now one of the first Co-Creator Officers for Faraday Future with their FF91 2.0 Futurist Alliance!

The vehicle blew me away when I saw it, as in reality it is the creation of a new category of silicon-based species, known as the "All-Ability aiHypercar," which has paved the way for the development of their first vehicle model, the FF 91 2.0 Futurist Alliance.

Luxury combined with leading-edge technology is the vision, and as someone that loves driving, helping develop the performance side of the car is something I am looking forward to.

I will be involved in many areas of the project, including introducing the vehicle to the world of luxury events and motorsports!

Stay tuned for some incredible content coming soon, as the future is already here!

Part 1/3

An old mans world.
Le Mans and La Chartre sur Le Loir 
Summer 2023

Curiosity is a dying trait.
I am as guilty as the next person when it comes to exploring outside of my immediate comfort zone.
Not because I fear the unknown, but because it takes effort and time, and it is easier to conjure up an excuse than use either of those precious commodities.
So, like most of us, I often miss out.

My partner Mailani, is however, not a casualty of such laziness when it come to exploration.
Wherever we go, she urges me on to take an extra hour or day, to learn more about a place we are visiting. 
Her enthusiasm for adventure is contagious.
I am re-visiting places I have been many times , now to discover sights unseen. I eat at places I would have previously passed by. I take walks through streets where before I would have run.
It’s beautiful.

Which brings me to this story.
On the Sunday of the 100th running of the Le Mans 24 Hour this past June, we returned to the little village of La Chartre sur Le Loir (where my family have stayed for decades), tired from the long day at the track but energized from the grand spectacle that is Le Mans.
Before we met everyone for dinner, we decided to take a walk alongside the river where I used to play as a kid, my Leica in hand.
It was so picturesque that life that day felt “as good as it gets”.
But it got even better.

Part 2/3
An old mans world

Heading back to the hotel, walking down the closed market street, we stopped at the window of a small Ateliers that had caught our eye. Two shop windows next to each other, one with paintings and the other pottery. There were these beautiful tiles on display, the same as the ones we had seen all around town on houses. Gentle details of peoples lives, like calling cards on the unseen inhabitants. The butcher, the lawyer, the baker, the family home with sunbathing felines. 
As we turned to head back for dinner, we heard a tap on the other side of the dusty glass window, the door cracked open and an old mans face emerged from the gloomy interior. More than a little surprised, we smiled back and then he waved us to come in. “Entrez. Entrez”.
Total strangers on a Sunday in France being invited into this mans private world. 
So of course, we went in.

The next hour was one of the most magical I have had in many years.  It is so difficult to describe eloquently enough to do the memory justice. Our French is rudimentary and the old mans English non-existent, yet we communicated well in a language of kinship and open friendship.

Apparently, Monsieur Michel Boillot had bought the property over 50 years ago with his wife, Jeanne-Noelle, when they moved from Paris to have a family.
They were both artists and while his wife continued to paint in her studio, he moved on to make ceramics and create the beautiful tiles we had seen in the region.

He was so gentle, gracious, kind and welcoming as he shuffled from crowded room to room, showing us his life work. We visited his studio at the rear of the building where his kiln was still at full heat.
His powdered glazes and brushes sat on the window ledge as they had for decades, not as a display, but as working instruments of a lifetimes passion of creativity.

Cont…..

Part 3/3

We then moved into his wife’s half of the building, where her prolific body of work covered every available surface. Scenes from lives led and imaginations fed, from her perspective. 
Finally, he led us to her art studio where it appeared she had just stopped painting moments before we arrived.
With a sadness that we both felt, Monsieur Boillot told us his wife had died a year before, and he had left everything untouched. 
Time stopped and paint laden brushes and palettes were laid down on her easel, as if by her hand moments ago.
I can tell you, tears were in my eyes, as this lovely old man revealed more details of their life together.
It was a life long love affair and they remained devoted to each other long after their children grew up and had their own families.
He told us the house had been so full of life and happiness, now it was just him, inviting total strangers in to make new memories and to share the old ones.

Walking towards a small building next to the flowing Loire River, the garden overgrown, Mailani and I held hands as we watched this frail old man leading the way, seemingly moving between his inner thoughts and telling us about their life on the property, stopping to point out hidden treasures. 
But the old man was full of surprises and as he opened the door on what looked like a giant dollhouse, a set of rustic very old keys hanging along the door sill, it was as though we had time travelled! 

The light was fading fast and it was our time to take leave. Suddenly, he bent over to pick up something from the path, the smallest strawberry I’ve ever seen. I have no idea how his old eyes spotted it. He seemed so happy to find this tiny sign of summers fruit and show it to us. He held out his hand and gave the tiny crimson fruit to Mailani to enjoy with a delicate smile. “Le premier de l’anee”.
It was so intimate, and I think we both felt like we were intruding on the last moments of a beautiful day.
As he showed us the door, we both hugged him and when we said we will be back to visit him next year, he looked into our eyes and smiled without a hint of sadness and said; “Thank you. But probably not”.

Edited beautifully by Mailani.

What a sad moment in time.
The loss of a true friend. 
A brotherhood, based on shared passions, experiences, understanding, honesty, and a liking for barely wearing clothes around the house.
I will miss the hours of beautiful bullshit we talked deep into the night. Sometimes brilliant, mostly insightful, and always under the influence, but you gave such great council, I felt special in that moment. We all did who shared times like this with you. You believed in my future more than I did at times, and I could tell you had put real thought into our conversations, before you came back to me with your opinion.
I wish you had taken more of my advice on certain things but you would smile and say what will be will be, and that you weren’t destined to get old. You asshole. You were right once again. But that quick end you hoped for is about 20 years too soon!

Your beautiful family are devastated, but with the kind of love between them that they will be ok in the end. The massive hole you leave is another thing my friend, (I’m not just taking about your robust silhouette) and we will all struggle to fill that void. 

There is much more to say about you but those words need a bit of time to materialize from the filter of grief.

But I have so many things I still want to tell you so I’ll sit up tonight and do just that. You were always a great listener so why stop now. 

You were one hell of a racing driver. But an even better human and friend.
I already miss you Couchon.
JB
Host of Drive To Wynn Las Vegas, The Torque Show, Life with Legends.
